---
import DocsLayout from "../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import CodeBlock from "../../../components/docs/CodeBlock.astro";

const toc = [
  { id: "when", label: "When to use it", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "how", label: "How to write it", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "emitted", label: "What gets emitted", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "html", label: "Plain HTML works too", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "static", label: "The static-subtree rule", level: 2 as const },
];
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Inline SVG"
  description="Hand-written <svg> inside a container wrapper. Babel rewrites the viewBox at compile time so the perceptual shift lives in the asset, not on the element."
  toc={toc}
>
  <h2 id="when">When to use it</h2>
  <p>
    Pick this when the icon's markup is authored by hand in the same
    file — a designer hand-off, a glyph you sketched in
    <code>{`<svg>`}</code> directly, an SVG snippet pasted from a
    figma export. No icon-component library involved.
  </p>

  <h2 id="how">How to write it</h2>
  <p>
    Wrap the <code>{`<svg>`}</code> in a container with
    <code>optical-center="auto"</code>:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    filename="PlayBadge.tsx"
    lang="tsx"
    code={`export function PlayBadge() {
  return (
    <div optical-center="auto">
      <svg
        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
        fill="none"
        stroke="currentColor"
        strokeWidth="2"
        strokeLinecap="round"
        strokeLinejoin="round"
      >
        <polygon points="6 3 20 12 6 21 6 3" />
      </svg>
    </div>
  );
}`}
  />

  <h2 id="emitted">What gets emitted</h2>
  <p>
    For a hand-written inline SVG, Babel doesn't need to look up an
    asset path or emit a <code>translate</code> — it rewrites the
    SVG's <code>viewBox</code> directly. The perceptual shift becomes
    part of the asset.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    filename="dist/PlayBadge-*.js"
    lang="jsx"
    code={`<div style={{ display: 'flex' }} data-optical-center="">
  <svg
    viewBox="-0.3239 -0.6226 24 24"
    data-optical-center=""
    fill="none"
    stroke="currentColor"
    strokeWidth="2"
    strokeLinecap="round"
    strokeLinejoin="round"
  >
    <polygon points="6 3 20 12 6 21 6 3" />
  </svg>
</div>`}
  />

  <p>
    Note the difference vs the <a href="/docs/patterns/jsx-attribute">JSX
    attribute</a> pattern with an icon component: there, the child kept
    its original SVG and picked up a <code>translate</code>. Here, the
    child's <code>viewBox</code> shifted and there's no
    <code>translate</code> on the icon. Both produce the same visual
    result; the difference is just where the shift lives.
  </p>

  <h2 id="html">Plain HTML works too</h2>
  <p>
    Same pattern outside JSX. Vite's HTML transform (and the Astro
    integration's post-build sweep) rewrite the
    <code>{`<svg>`}</code>'s <code>viewBox</code> in place:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    filename="index.html"
    lang="html"
    code={`<div optical-center="auto">
  <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor">
    <polygon points="6 3 20 12 6 21 6 3" />
  </svg>
</div>`}
  />

  <p>
    For HTML the marker on the <code>{`<svg>`}</code> itself is also
    accepted as a lower-level shortcut:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    filename="index.html"
    lang="html"
    code={`<svg optical-center viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor">
  <polygon points="6 3 20 12 6 21 6 3" />
</svg>`}
  />

  <h2 id="static">The static-subtree rule</h2>
  <p>
    Babel rewrites a hand-written SVG only if the entire subtree is
    statically known at compile time. That means:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>No spread attributes anywhere in the tree (<code>{`<svg {...rest}>`}</code>).</li>
    <li>No <code>{`{expression}`}</code> children inside the SVG.</li>
    <li>No fragments around or inside the SVG.</li>
    <li>No conditional rendering that produces different SVG shapes per render.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If the validator can't prove the subtree is static, the plugin bails
    out with <code>OPTICAL_DYNAMIC_SVG</code> and leaves the markup
    untouched. Duplicate the literal SVG across branches if you need
    conditionals — pulling it through any indirection trips the
    validator.
  </p>

  <aside class="callout">
    <p class="callout-label">Why so strict</p>
    <p>
      The rewrite is read-only first, mutate second. Babel serializes
      the JSX subtree to an SVG string, rasterizes it, runs the
      centering pipeline, computes the new <code>viewBox</code>, and
      only then mutates the AST. If anything in the subtree could
      change at runtime, the build-time rasterization wouldn't match
      what the browser eventually paints — and a near-correct shift
      is worse than no shift.
    </p>
  </aside>
</DocsLayout>
